			<div class="content" id="post-content-4045297">
									

<p>Ah, that explains it not being obvious. I'm rather green with the whole wikidot code stuff. Seems we have rather a proliferation of standards these days, between multiple flavours of HTML, CSS, Javascript, PHP-MySQL, BBCode, wikipedia markup, markdown, and now this. But it is at least largely one of the more logical and readable formats, and seems to be - through those module inclusions - extremely powerful and flexible.</p>
<p>Bones I'm now going to read as talking like Data from STTNG, as he tends towards a similar verbal affect ;)</p>
<p>I know couple can sometimes be used for more than two, but on an international standpoint it does also carry the direct meaning of a (not necessarily matched) pair, or at least an uncertain number in that region (1 to 3, or less often (1 or) 2 to 4); &quot;(a) few&quot; is more general on that front, though potentially even more ambiguous - &quot;several&quot; may work, though again which of the two is larger may depend on your locale. In my own it's couple-few-several(-many-lots) but I know it can vary. So I hope I haven't messed up your text too much with that question.</p>

